{{main|2009 swine flu outbreak by country}}
[[Image:H1N1 Costa Rica Map.svg|thumb|right|200px|Costa Rica {{legend|#000000|Confirmed cases followed by death}}{{legend|#FF0000|Confirmed cases}}{{legend|#FFA900|Unconfirmed or suspected cases}}]]

In March and April 2009, an [[2009 swine flu outbreak|outbreak of a new strain of flu]] (also known as influenza), popularly known as "[[swine flu]]" was discovered to have infected several people in [[Mexico]] and the states of [[California]] and [[Texas]] in the [[United States]]. On April 28 [[Costa Rica]] became the first [[Central America]]n country to report the outbreak of the virus, with a confirmed infection.<ref name="ticos1">{{cite web|url=http://www.nacion.com/ln_ee/2009/abril/28/pais1948013.html|title=Confirmada primera tica con fiebre porcina|publisher=[[La Naci<U+00F3>n (Costa Rica)|La Naci<U+00F3>n]]|accessdate=2009-04-28|language=Spanish}}</ref> By May 19 Costa Rica had nine confirmed cases of influenza A (H1N1), leading to one fatality,<ref name="ticos5">{{cite web|url=http://www.clarin.com/diario/2009/05/09/um/m-01914830.htm|title=Gripe porcina: Costa Rica confirm<U+00F3> la muerte de un hombre a causa de la enfermedad|publisher=[[Clar<U+00ED>n]]|date=2009-05-09|accessdate=2009-05-09|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name="ticos6">{{cite web|url=http://www.nacion.com/ln_ee/2009/mayo/09/pais1959686.html|title=Muere primer tico contagiado de gripe AH1N1|publisher=[[La Naci<U+00F3>n (Costa Rica)|La Naci<U+00F3>n]]|date=2009-05-09|accessdate=2009-05-09|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name="ticos8"/> 13 probable cases pending confirmation, 128 suspected, and 891 already discarded.<ref name="ticosLatest">{{cite web|url=http://www.ministeriodesalud.go.cr/emergencia_sanitaria/boletines/comunicado_oficial_influenza_pandemica_19_de_mayo_2009.pdf|format=pdf|title=Comunicado Oficial: Situaci<U+00F3>n de la Influenza Pand<U+00E9>mica en Costa Rica |publisher=Ministerio de Salud de Costa Rica |date=2009-05-19 |accessdate=2009-05-20|language=Spanish}}</ref> 

==Outbreak==
The first confirmed case of influenza A (H1N1) in Costa Rica was announced on April 28, and was that of a young woman hospitalized in San Jose.<ref name="ticos1"/> On April 28, Minister of Health of Costa Rica, Maria Luisa Avila confirmed the second case, a 29-year old man hospitalized at the Hospital San Vicente de Paul in [[San Francisco de Heredia|Heredia]].<ref name="ticos2">{{cite web|url=http://www.nacion.com/ln_ee/2009/abril/28/pais1948709.html|title=Confirmado segundo tico con fiebre porcina|publisher=[[La Naci<U+00F3>n (Costa Rica)|La Naci<U+00F3>n]]|date=2009-04-28|accessdate=2009-04-28|language=Spanish}}</ref> A National Health Emergency was announced. Another potential case, that of a patient in [[San Carlos Canton|San Carlos]], was not confirmed.

The Ministry of Health reported the existence of two new probable cases of swine flu in the country on the morning of May 2.<ref name="ticos3">{{cite web|url=http://www.nacion.com/ln_ee/2009/mayo/02/pais1952519.html|title=Salud reporta dos nuevos casos de gripe porcina en el pa<U+00ED>s|publisher=[[La Naci<U+00F3>n (Costa Rica)|La Naci<U+00F3>n]]|date=2009-04-30|accessdate=2009-05-02|language=Spanish}}</ref> These were a 53-year old man who had not traveled to Mexico, in a hospital in San Jose, and a 24-year old woman who is recovering at home. These new patients brought the total number of Costa Ricans affected by the virus to four. Three are listed as probable cases, while one was duly confirmed by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] in the United States. Four more cases were confirmed on May 4 by the Costa Rican "''Centro Nacional de Referencia en Virolog<U+00ED>a''." As of May 4, a total of 424 suspected cases have been reported, but 369 have been already discarded as swine flu.<ref name="ticos4"/> All of these patients have recently traveled to Mexico. Since April 29 the Ministry of Health recommended to avoid travel to Mexico, [[Canada]], and the U.S. as the number of confirmed cases by local authorities reached eight.<ref name="ticos4">{{cite web|url=http://www.nacion.com/ln_ee/2009/mayo/04/pais1954697.html|title=Sube a ocho cifra de ticos infectados con gripe pand<U+00E9>mica|publisher=[[La Naci<U+00F3>n (Costa Rica)|La Naci<U+00F3>n]]|date=2009-05-04|accessdate=2009-05-04|language=Spanish}}</ref>

On May 12 the Minister of Health announced that an alert was received from U.S. authorities informing that three members from a [[Boston]] chorus, Canta Mundi, that traveled to several tourism places in Costa Rica during April, showed symptoms of AH1N1 flu after returning to the U.S.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nacion.com/ln_ee/2009/mayo/12/pais1961617.html|publisher=[[La Naci<U+00F3>n (Costa Rica)|La Naci<U+00F3>n]]|title=Coro de Boston viaj<U+00F3> por todo el pa<U+00ED>s con la gripe AH1N1|date=2009-05-12|accessdate=2009-05-14|language=Spanish}}</ref> On May 13 Costa Rican health authorities announced four new probable cases, three of which had contact with the Boston chorus, and a follow-up is being done with those who had contact with the chorus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nacion.com/ln_ee/2009/mayo/13/pais1963647.html|publisher=[[La Naci<U+00F3>n (Costa Rica)|La Naci<U+00F3>n]]|title=Salud reporta cuatro nuevos casos probables de gripe|date=2009-05-13|accessdate=2009-05-14|language=Spanish}}</ref> A couple of English language newspapers questioned whether the chorus members had infected locals, or rather the Boston youngsters picked up the disease in Costa Rica, as the chorus flew directly from the United States to Costa Rica.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amcostarica.com/tuesday.htm|publisher=A.M. Costa Rica|title=Boston chorus getting blame for spreading swine flu|date=2009-05-13|accessdate=2009-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wickedlocal.com/lexington/news/lifestyle/health/x1194170001/Costa-Rica-blames-singers-for-swine-flu-spread|publisher=Wicked Local Lexington|title=UPDATE: Costa Rica blames singers for swine flu spread|date=2009-05-13|accessdate=2009-05-15}}</ref>

==Deaths==
The Ministry of Health received confirmation on the night of Friday May 8 from the Centers for Disease Control of seven cases of infection with influenza A/H1N1 virus. Health Minister Maria Luisa Avila announced that these were three men, aged 24, 30 and 53, two women, aged 20 and 25, two girls, aged 4 and 11, and a boy aged 3. "They are people who were in Mexico or had contact with travelers to that country", said the Ministry. The 53-year old man became the first fatality in Costa Rica, confirmed on the morning of Saturday, May 9 by the Minister of Health.<ref name="ticos5"/><ref name="ticos6"/><ref name="ticos8"/>

Out of the seven remaining cases confirmed by the US [[Center for Disease Control]], three are children infected by the patient who died, and their condition is not critical.<ref name="ticos7">{{cite web|url=http://www.nacion.com/ln_ee/2009/mayo/09/pais1959751.html|title=Tres ni<U+00F1>os con gripe AH1N1 fueron contagiados por tico que falleci<U+00F3> esta madrugada|publisher=[[La Naci<U+00F3>n (Costa Rica)|La Naci<U+00F3>n]]|date=2009-05-09|accessdate=2009-05-09|language=Spanish}}</ref> Costa Rica became the fourth country in the world, after Mexico, the United States and Canada to confirm fatalities related to the influenza virus A (H1N1).<ref name="ticos8">{{cite web|url=http://www.abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory?id=7545376|title=Costa Rica Sees 1st Swine Flu Death|publisher=[[ABC News]]|date=2009-05-09|accessdate=2009-05-09}}</ref>

The deceased man was suffering other chronic diseases. The Minister of Health informed he had [[diabetes]] and also was suffering from [[chronic obstructive pulmonary disease]] (COPD). She also informed the man was infected inside Costa Rica because he had not traveled to Mexico, and that a total 51 persons were identified who had contact with the sick man, but only three turned out positive.<ref name="ticos9">{{cite web|url=http://www.nacion.com/ln_ee/2009/mayo/09/pais1959688.html|title=Tico fallecido por gripe AH1N1 empeor<U+00F3> por enfermedades cr<U+00F3>nicas|publisher=[[La Naci<U+00F3>n (Costa Rica)|La Naci<U+00F3>n]]|date=2009-05-09|accessdate=2009-05-11|language=Spanish}}</ref>

